cs.IT, cs.DS, cs.SI, cs.LG, cs.CC. 

This paper deals with information theory and communication, specifically the problem of channel resolvability for discrete memoryless channels. Therefore, cs.IT (Information Theory) is the most likely sub-category. The paper also involves mathematical analysis and optimization, which could fall under cs.DS (Data Structures and Algorithms) and cs.LG (Machine Learning). The use of probability and statistics could also place it under cs.SI (Social and Information Networks). Finally, the paper involves the study of capacity achieving input distributions, which could fall under cs.CC (Computational Complexity).
